I mean this to help you all in the future. I'm fairly sure a 14-YEAR OLD pregnant Mary  wasn't this chill about the most important birth in ALL OF HISTORY. Neither was Joseph. I know this is marketed to children, but it's way too "Disney-ish." Don't get me wrong, I really do appreciate Affirm Films' work, I really do. But this is such a dumbing down of The Virgin birth of God Incarnate that kids will be talking about a hip Hop Dove and not The Messiah! I'll be fine with The Nativity Story...

text: Next to Prince of Egypt and Joseph King of Dreams, I've been waiting for some good comedic yet accurate depiction of a Bible story. So far it looks good and I don't know why people are overreacting just because it's delightfully told from the perspective of a donkey which is God's creation.    If you aren't Christian, I get why you aren't excited.    But even nonreligious people can understand how crappy Christian film has been for a while now, and most of the best and beloved Christian films are done by secular studios.    So I don't see what's so objectionable in doctrine.  Honestly.  The creators have shown no sign of slander or hate or disrespect towards the actual Gospel. They have maintained a reverence for the Messiah, and that is RARE for a secular media house in 2017.   I appreciate this.

text: They could have told a beautiful rendition of an age old religious tale with real artistic value, a la Prince of Egypt. Instead they're clearly aiming for a generic, dull, blatantly manufactured family comedy on par with Sing or Norm of the North. The only difference is it has a religious context, but only enough so as not to scare off any hypersensitive viewers. Even the characters look incredibly bland and uninspired. I'm not religious but still, the story deserves respect and dignity. If they really have to make it a comedy out of it, can't they at least pull back on the slapstick and do something more clever and less tone deaf? Can someone please call Disney?
